  "prompt": "If I filled a weather balloon with helium only to 75 percent of the balloon's holding capacity, would it ease into higher altitudes without popping?",
  "response": "Yes, filling a weather balloon to 75 percent of its holding capacity with helium is a common practice to ensure that it can ascend to higher altitudes without popping. As the balloon rises, the atmospheric pressure decreases, causing the helium gas inside the balloon to expand. If the balloon were filled to its maximum capacity on the ground, this expansion could cause the balloon to burst as it ascends. By filling it to only 75 percent, you allow room for the gas to expand safely, reducing the risk of the balloon popping as it reaches higher elevations. This method is standard procedure for launching weather balloons and other high-altitude balloons.",
